Besides being the de facto founder of Continental philosophy

Hegel's immanent critique (which includes dialectics) is the single most impactful philosophy ive ever read. And without it Marx wouldn't even be a thing!
He revolutionized epistemology by bringing in an intersectional analysis of culture and history, his philosophy is completely presuppositionless, he ended skepticism, he ended the subject/object distinction, he succeeded in giving an account of how objective knowledge is possible

Author: omnomswag
Content: people often mistake marxists as having a predetermined historical outlook that whatever we do history progresses as it is, that the masses have nothing to do in shaping our future, but even by marxs standard he was ambivalent at best in that case, it was actually engels who vehemently believed in this "historical determinism" both at first held similar views upon it but when marx died engels drifted more and more into the determonist camp. a growing group of intelligentsia based socialist movement in russia, the narodniks largely rejected this view of a predetermined history, that societies of all shapes and sizes progresses the same as the next, and in popular culture people try to frame it as marxist being the "objectivists" and the russian narodniks as being "subjectivist" while this is true to an extent marxs' historical determinism himself was weak and isn't nearly backed with enough evidence that he himself does not support other theories of historical development, only that he's most familiar with the historical development of western europe. russian marxist georgy plekhanov often dubbed the father of russian marxism also doesn't held the view of historical determinism that not all societies has or had gone through the same path of development only that russia is developing western european style of development and so why not continue it since it is the most familiar type of development. freewill exist in marxism!

Content:
There is no amount of word limits on earth that u can utilize to prop up liberal democracies as being inherently more democratic than soviet democracy, but first of all, i dont support soviet democracy just trying to set the record straight about it.

in soviet democracy candidates can and did come from all walks of life, money isn't an issue in soviet democracies and its "peripheries" (cuba, mongolia etc) unlike in liberal democracy where candidates are expected to fork over literal millions just to be able to engage in politics, and theres no disenable system of replacing candidates either once voted in part due to the access of wealth that they posses. in the early years of the soviet union a system of recall was routinely practiced this can range from village level officials recalling those from up in national level officials out of their offices' that is the answer to your question "how is soviet democracy a realer form of democracy if it restricts voters to one party and curbs on the influence of bourgeois movements?" the one party lets poor people in thats a luxury that most bourgeois parties dont offer even to this day, and this is just basic entryism and i only manage to dive into the recall process.

democracy isn't a system within itself, it is a the basis for political organizations and structures to be formed upon. soviet democracy restricts the influence of the bourgeoisie and liberal democracy restricts the influence of the proletariat, which voter base makes up a majority in any given country? the people who enslave you or the slaves.

Author: Deleted User
Content:
The issue of money within liberal democracy is an issue, that's a fair point, but that doesn't justify Soviet democracies as being more democratic. Germany, the United Kingdom, France, for example, has laws against unduly influencing an election by money. Candidates are given a strict money purse and must not expend past that for campaigns and so on. While that *doesn't* eliminate the issue of money, that does mitigate it somewhat. Even if we accept that, it does not mean that when we turn around, Soviet democracy is somehow better. village-level officials recalling national ones out of office. That simply does not happen. 

The Soviet system worked like this: Citizens elect their local council who then elects the regional council who then elects the provincial council who then elects the Supreme Soviet or the national legislature. Thing is, with so many intermediaries between the citizens and the nation's rulers, you cannot hold them to account. Okay, say your provincial governor is fucking wild. He's doing shit you don't approve of even though what he's doing is fine by the Party. What can I do? Take it up with my local council? That person has to take it up with the regional council, and there's no guarantee that (a) my complaint will be delivered, (b) that it will even be heard, and (c) that the regional council then does something for that. In a liberal democracy, I can easily vote against that governor when the next election comes up.

How does Soviet democracy restrict the bourgeoisie if there is no mechanism in which the citizens are able to hold their representatives into account? If the Party got infected by bourgeois elements, how can I fight against that? How can I prevent that? You can't. Why? Because anyone who wants to run for office has to be approved by the Party. See the error? The Party perpetuates itself. I have no voice because I have no choice.

Author: jaxxxxxxyyyy
Content:
so to answer your question properly, it is a quote by Rene Descartes

Basically this statement is meant for to answer a philosophical question of how we can verify our existence. How can we ensure that our existence isn't just some simulation, illusion or even a lie in the first place. Rene Descartes stated that "I think, therefore I am," which suggested that we do exist since our existence was marked by the question of our existence alone. 

if one is able to think, even to doubt, then they must exist as a thinking entity, which suggest that their existence is not one of a lie.

Author: kaviarormonroe
Content:
He means that you can doubt everything in the world except for the fact that youre doubting and ergo that you (as a thinking thing) exists. because if you wouldnt exist then there wouldn't be anyone to do the doubting which descartes sees as a contradiction
> I will suppose, then, that everything I see is fictitious. I will believe that my memory tells me nothing but lies. I have no senses. Body, shape, extension, movement and place are illusions. So what remains true? (...) If I convinced myself of something then I certainly existed.
> But there is a supremely powerful and cunning deceiver who deliberately deceives me all the time! Even then, if he is deceiving me I undoubtedly exist: let him deceive me all he can, he will never bring it about that I am nothing while I think I am something. So after thoroughly thinking the matter through I conclude that this proposition, I am, I exist, must be true whenever I assert it or think it.
the "he" refers to a supremely powerful demon that deceives descartes about everything
its a device for him to doubt things such as mathematics
